{
  "success": true,
  "data": {
    "query": "CAISO regulation service participation requirements business process manual market operations regulation service participation requirements BPM Market Operations latest",
    "num_results": 10,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": "CAISO",
      "data_type": "report",
      "year_start": 2018,
      "year_end": 2026,
      "range_type": "lte"
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "4b2c284a-cf9a-4d57-a0af-d4fb20b8f0ca",
        "score": 0.54244125,
        "text": "The document is from the Department of Market Monitoring for the California ISO, dated August 2021. It discusses the first phase of a stakeholder process addressing three key areas: resource sufficiency, provision of transmission, and allocation of congestion rents. \n\n1. **Resource Sufficiency**: The extended day-ahead market design must allow entities to meet resource sufficiency obligations with power from resources scheduled over another balancing authority's transmission. Concerns are raised about the proposed firm transmission requirement, which could restrict transmission availability, affecting resource sufficiency.\n\n2. **Provision of Transmission**: The Western EIM is a voluntary market where transmission operators could offer unreserved transmission to the extended day-ahead market. While this could increase transmission availability, there are concerns about its impact on competitive access. The DMM suggests further consideration of mechanisms to ensure competitive access.\n\n3. **Congestion Revenues**: The allocation of congestion rents is crucial for incentivizing transmission provision. Allocating these rents to transmission owners could encourage them to make transmission available, but the allocation method needs careful consideration to ensure effectiveness.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2020/page_307.jpg",
          "page_num": 307,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2020,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "8ad24eee-183b-4e69-a4a2-d3881db1db1d",
        "score": 0.538226,
        "text": "The document outlines the regulatory requirements and obligations for resource adequacy in the California ISO market. It details how the ISO collaborates with the CPUC and other authorities to set requirements for load-serving entities based on forecasted peak loads, including a planning reserve margin. Load-serving entities must demonstrate compliance through annual and monthly supply plans.\n\nFor annual showings, entities must prove they have procured 90% of their resource adequacy obligations for the summer months and 100% for monthly obligations. Plans are submitted to the ISO in advance of the compliance year or month.\n\nThe document also describes bidding and scheduling obligations. Scheduling coordinators must make resource adequacy capacity available in the ISO markets through:\n\n- **Day-ahead energy and ancillary services market**: All available capacity must be offered here.\n- **Residual unit commitment process**: Participants must submit bids priced at $0/MW.\n- **Real-time market**: Committed resources must be offered here, including short-start units.\n\nResource adequacy capacity not scheduled in the day-ahead market is not required in the real-time market unless specified. In 2018, half of the capacity was from resources that had to bid into the market each hour, except when unavailable due to outages.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2018/page_241.jpg",
          "page_num": 241,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2018,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "a0097aa5-aaad-48c5-8293-3ddbaeabf6b3",
        "score": 0.52710176,
        "text": "The document discusses the Department of Market Monitoring's (DMM) support for measures by the ISO to address transmission cost issues and market power in the California ISO markets. It highlights the need for a voluntary market for financial contracts to manage transmission costs. The DMM recommends actions to mitigate system market power, which affects market costs and reliability. Key recommendations include:\n\n1. Exploring options for market power mitigation.\n2. Setting high resource adequacy requirements.\n3. Reevaluating import provisions and must-offer obligations.\n4. Strengthening penalties for non-compliance.\n5. Monitoring for errors affecting market power mitigation.\n\nIn 2018, the ISO began analyzing its system's competitiveness to consider further mitigation strategies.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2018/page_275.jpg",
          "page_num": 275,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2018,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "99af6c54-4cc4-4c0a-becc-cd5cc7b17222",
        "score": 0.5171357,
        "text": "The document discusses the Department of Market Monitoring's (DMM) recommendations to address system market power in California's ISO market. It highlights the need for new market design options to mitigate potential market power impacts on costs and reliability. DMM suggests a filing at FERC to ensure imports exceeding $1,000/MWh are subject to cost verification, preventing unchecked imports up to $2,000/MWh.\n\nThe document also addresses reliability must-run (RMR) units, emphasizing the need for sufficient capacity to maintain system reliability. DMM criticizes RMR Condition 2 contracts as inefficient and costly, recommending changes to ensure RMR resources are subject to must-offer requirements with cost-based bids. The ISO initiated a stakeholder process in 2018 to consider these changes, and in March 2019, the ISO Board approved tariff modifications to address these issues.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2018/page_33.jpg",
          "page_num": 33,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2018,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "1d64a286-9f4e-411a-b804-cbec332ec1d1",
        "score": 0.5065343,
        "text": "The document is from the Department of Market Monitoring for California ISO, dated July 2024. It discusses the requirements for load-serving entities to procure capacity to meet planning reserve margins (PRM) between 20 and 22.5 percent. These entities must file annual and monthly supply plans with the California ISO.\n\nFor annual supply plans, CPUC-jurisdictional load-serving entities must show they have procured 90% of their system resource adequacy obligations for the five summer months of the upcoming compliance year. For monthly supply plans, they must demonstrate 100% procurement of their monthly obligations.\n\nTable 8.1 (not shown) details recent CPUC decisions affecting resource adequacy in 2023. Footnotes explain the PRM reflects operating reserve requirements and additional capacity for outages and forecast errors, and reference CPUC decision D.21-12-015 for more details on procurement requirements.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2023/page_278.jpg",
          "page_num": 278,
          "title": "2023 Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "f790fd58-bd60-4997-a18b-eef8bd3b015e",
        "score": 0.4997707,
        "text": "The document page from the Department of Market Monitoring \u2013 California ISO, dated August 2021, discusses the procurement and scheduling obligations for resource adequacy in the energy market. Key points include:\n\n1. **Annual and Monthly Supply Plans**: CPUC-jurisdictional load-serving entities must demonstrate procurement of 90% of their system resource adequacy obligations for the five summer months annually, and 100% for monthly obligations.\n\n2. **Bidding and Scheduling Obligations**:\n   - **Day-ahead Market**: All available resource adequacy capacity must be bid into the day-ahead market, including those certified for ancillary services.\n   - **Residual Unit Commitment Process**: Participants must submit bids priced at $0/MW for all resource adequacy capacity.\n   - **Real-time Market**: Resources committed in the day-ahead or residual unit commitment process must also be offered in real-time markets. Long-start units and imports not scheduled in prior processes are not required to bid in real-time.\n\n3. **Capacity Procurement in 2020**: About 43% of the capacity was from resources not use-limited and bid into ISO markets continuously, mainly gas-fired. The remaining capacity was from resources with operating limitations like hydro, nuclear, wind, and solar.\n\n4. **Bid Data Processing**: For generic resource adequacy, day-ahead bids include energy and non-overlapping ancillary services, while real-time bids include energy only. Bids are capped at resource adequacy capacity values.\n\nThe document emphasizes the importance of meeting resource adequacy requirements through structured bidding and scheduling processes.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2020/page_257.jpg",
          "page_num": 257,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2020,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "281b2b6c-2f60-46fa-8cdd-f9060c54a53a",
        "score": 0.49841475,
        "text": "The document is from the Department of Market Monitoring at California ISO, dated May 2019. It discusses the integration of certain units into the resource adequacy program, eliminating the need for reliability must-run contracts. In 2018, the ISO began a stakeholder process to reform the reliability must-run policy. The Department of Market Monitoring (DMM) provided recommendations to enhance the policy's effectiveness alongside the CPUC's resource adequacy program. New tariff provisions from this process were filed on April 22, 2019.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2018/page_268.jpg",
          "page_num": 268,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2018,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "002fefba-2a34-4988-bdb0-122954147651",
        "score": 0.49737424,
        "text": "The document discusses the California ISO's procurement of ancillary services in day-ahead and real-time markets, including regulation up, regulation down, spinning reserves, and non-spinning reserves. These services must meet or exceed standards set by the Western Electricity Coordinating Council and the North American Electric Reliability Corporation. The ISO aims to procure all services in the day-ahead market as much as possible.\n\nAncillary services are procured from various regions, including internal and expanded sub-regions, with requirements identical to internal regions but including interties. Services procured in a more inward region also count towards the outer region's requirements. Both internal resources and imports meet these requirements.\n\nHistorically, only four regions were used for procurement, but since December 14, 2017, expanded and internal North of Path 26 region requirements have been met to match South of Path 26 requirements. This change was made to facilitate the distribution of ancillary services.\n\nOperating reserve requirements in the day-ahead market are based on the highest of three factors: 6.3% of the load forecast, the most severe single contingency, or 15% of forecasted solar production. Real-time requirements use 3% of the load forecast and generation instead of 6.3%. These requirements are split between spinning and non-spinning reserves.\n\nThe Federal Energy Regulatory Commission introduced new requirements effective January 1, 2018, under BAL-002-2, requiring reevaluation of the most severe single contingency. The Pacific DC Intertie was grouped as a credible contingency for this purpose.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2018/page_155.jpg",
          "page_num": 155,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2018,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "8407a698-9d87-4c50-9d2e-4cc9026ed24a",
        "score": 0.49548665,
        "text": "The document is an annual report on market issues and performance by the Department of Market Monitoring for California ISO, dated May 2019. It includes the following sections:\n\n1. **Flexible Ramping and Energy Imbalance**: Discusses tests and relaxations related to flexible ramping and energy imbalance market power balance constraints, as well as greenhouse gas considerations and available balancing capacity.\n\n2. **Convergence Bidding**: Covers trends, payments, and cost recovery charges related to convergence bidding.\n\n3. **Ancillary Services**: Details costs, requirements, procurement, pricing, scarcity, and compliance testing of ancillary services.\n\n4. **Market Competitiveness and Mitigation**: Analyzes the competitiveness of day-ahead markets, bids for gas-fired units, and transmission constraints. It also covers local market power mitigation and exceptional dispatches.\n\n5. **Congestion**: Provides background on congestion, its impact on locational prices, and congestion revenue rights, including auctioned rights and returns.\n\n6. **Market Adjustments**: Discusses exceptional dispatch, manual dispatches, load adjustments, residual unit commitment adjustments, and blocked instructions and dispatches.\n\nEach section provides detailed insights into specific aspects of market operations and performance within the California ISO framework.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2018/page_6.jpg",
          "page_num": 6,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2018,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "36148068-93fe-4cbc-8a43-2f988cb53d79",
        "score": 0.49505973,
        "text": "The document discusses two main topics related to the California ISO's market operations:\n\n1. **Commitment Cost and Default Energy Bid Enhancements (CCDEBE):**\n   - Implemented on February 16, 2021, this policy allows resources to adjust their commitment costs to submit start-up or minimum-load bids above a certain threshold.\n   - The process can be automated or manual, based on the resource's bid and reasonableness threshold, which includes a multiplier for fuel cost variability.\n   - Automated requests are used for costs within the threshold, while manual requests are needed for costs above it, requiring evidence of higher costs.\n   - In 2022, there was an increase in automated requests from gas resources, especially when gas prices spiked. Manual requests were fewer and often denied due to inadequate documentation.\n\n2. **Market-based Rate Authority in the Western Energy Imbalance Market (WEIM):**\n   - Participants under the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) jurisdiction must seek authority to sell at market-based rates in the WEIM.\n   - FERC reviews this authority triennially. Participants with granted market-based rate authority can sell in the WEIM, and those who pass the triennial review retain this authority.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2022/page_180.jpg",
          "page_num": 180,
          "title": "2022 Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2022,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

