        "text": "The document outlines the regulatory requirements and obligations for resource adequacy in the California ISO market. It details how the ISO collaborates with the CPUC and other authorities to set requirements for load-serving entities based on forecasted peak loads, including a planning reserve margin. Load-serving entities must demonstrate compliance through annual and monthly supply plans.\n\nFor annual showings, entities must prove they have procured 90% of their resource adequacy obligations for the summer months and 100% for monthly obligations. Plans are submitted to the ISO in advance of the compliance year or month.\n\nThe document also describes bidding and scheduling obligations. Scheduling coordinators must make resource adequacy capacity available in the ISO markets through:\n\n- **Day-ahead energy and ancillary services market**: All available capacity must be offered here.\n- **Residual unit commitment process**: Participants must submit bids priced at $0/MW.\n- **Real-time market**: Committed resources must be offered here, including short-start units.\n\nResource adequacy capacity not scheduled in the day-ahead market is not required in the real-time market unless specified. In 2018, half of the capacity was from resources that had to bid into the market each hour, except when unavailable due to outages.",
