        "score": 0.5153328,
        "text": "The document discusses the procurement of ancillary services by the ISO in day-ahead and real-time markets, focusing on regulation up, regulation down, spinning reserves, and non-spinning reserves. These services must meet standards set by the Western Electricity Coordinating Council and the North American Electric Reliability Corporation. The ISO procures services from 10 predefined regions, including internal and expanded sub-regions, with requirements ensuring internal and external resources meet minimum standards.\n\nHistorically, four regions were used for procurement, but since December 2017, expanded requirements have been applied to help distribute ancillary services more effectively. The document also outlines operating reserve requirements, which have been adjusted to comply with FERC Order No. 789 and WECC standards. These requirements are based on load forecasts and contingency scenarios, with reserves split between spinning and non-spinning. A report by the North American Electric Reliability Corporation highlighted a new reliability risk related to frequency measurement errors.",
