        "id": "698efa3a-2fc3-497b-9521-0ac7df3e78dd",
        "score": 0.5025914,
        "text": "The document page from the Department of Market Monitoring \u2013 California ISO, dated July 2022, discusses operating reserve requirements within the energy market. It explains that ancillary services are procured in nested internal sub-regions to meet the minimum requirements of broader regions. Six specific regions are mentioned for utilizing these services.\n\nOperating reserve requirements in the day-ahead market are determined by the highest of three factors: 6.3% of the load forecast, the most severe single contingency, or 15% of forecasted solar production. Real-time requirements are similar but use 3% of both the load forecast and generation. Reserves are split between spinning and non-spinning reserves.\n\nIn 2021, the average day-ahead operating reserve requirement was 1,770 MW, a 3% decrease from 2020. The document also references regulatory changes and standards related to reliability and contingency planning.",
