        "text": "The document page from the Department of Market Monitoring \u2013 California ISO, dated August 2021, discusses the procurement and scheduling obligations for resource adequacy in the energy market. Key points include:\n\n1. **Annual and Monthly Supply Plans**: CPUC-jurisdictional load-serving entities must demonstrate procurement of 90% of their system resource adequacy obligations for the five summer months annually, and 100% for monthly obligations.\n\n2. **Bidding and Scheduling Obligations**:\n   - **Day-ahead Market**: All available resource adequacy capacity must be bid into the day-ahead market, including those certified for ancillary services.\n   - **Residual Unit Commitment Process**: Participants must submit bids priced at $0/MW for all resource adequacy capacity.\n   - **Real-time Market**: Resources committed in the day-ahead or residual unit commitment process must also be offered in real-time markets. Long-start units and imports not scheduled in prior processes are not required to bid in real-time.\n\n3. **Capacity Procurement in 2020**: About 43% of the capacity was from resources not use-limited and bid into ISO markets continuously, mainly gas-fired. The remaining capacity was from resources with operating limitations like hydro, nuclear, wind, and solar.\n\n4. **Bid Data Processing**: For generic resource adequacy, day-ahead bids include energy and non-overlapping ancillary services, while real-time bids include energy only. Bids are capped at resource adequacy capacity values.\n\nThe document emphasizes the importance of meeting resource adequacy requirements through structured bidding and scheduling processes.",
